ent mode (similar to Cursor's Composer)\n  - AI semantic search with \"@ai\" commands\n  - Intelligent code refactoring with automatic reference updates\n- **Pricing**: $10-15/month (more affordable than Cursor)\n- **Strengths**: Smoother UI, faster performance, better value, more generous free tier\n\n### **Other AI IDE Competitors**\n\nThe search results mention a developing landscape including:\n- **Kiro**: Geared toward enterprise and complex task scenarios\n- **Zed**: Emphasizes editor performance and extensibility (base editor free, AI usage pay-per-token)\n- **Trae**: Another AI-native IDE option\n- **GitHub Copilot**: Plugin-based approach with extensive ecosystem\n\n## Market Context (2025-2026)\n\nThe search results indicate that by early 2026, the AI programming tool market has divided into two camps:\n\n1. **AI-first IDE Party** (Cursor, Windsurf): Deep AI integration with superior context understanding and multi-file refactoring\n2. **Plugin/Ecosystem Party** (GitHub Copilot, Tabnine, Amazon Q): Better compatibility with existing workflows\n\n**Key Note**: While the search results don't explicitly identify a specific AI IDE launched specifically in February 2025, the results show Windsurf and Cursor as the dominant players in the AI-native IDE space, with Windsurf being Cursor's primary alternative/competitor.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
