nAI officially released a new Codex desktop application for macOS** on February 2, 2026\n- The app focuses on **multi-agent workflows** and **agentic coding** capabilities\n- Features include:\n  - **Multi-agent parallel collaboration** - running multiple AI agents simultaneously\n  - **Automated task scheduling**\n  - **Customizable agent personalities**\n  - Integration of \"Agent Skills\" for orchestrating different specialized agents\n  - Deep integration into local development workflows\n\n### Apple Xcode 26.3 Update (February 3, 2026)\n- **Apple released Xcode 26.3** on February 3, 2026, introducing native **\"Agentic Coding\"** support\n- The update officially integrates **both Anthropic's Claude Agent and OpenAI's Codex** into Xcode\n- **Key capabilities**:\n  - Transforms Xcode from a passive editor to an active development partner\n  - Built-in tools for automatic planning, execution, and iterative development tasks\n  - **\"Vibe Coding\"** (intent-oriented programming) - developers describe requirements in natural language and AI generates complete, runnable code\n  - Support for visual interface analysis and Model Context Protocol (MCP)\n  - Apple worked closely with Anthropic and OpenAI to optimize token usage and tool calling mechanisms\n\n### Market Context\n- The releases mark a shift from \"AI assistant tools\" to **\"AI agent collaboration\"**\n- This positions OpenAI and Apple to compete more directly with tools like Cursor, GitHub Copilot, and Claude Code\n- Testing showed that zero-experience users could build a functional Pomodoro timer app with notifications and settings in just **2 minutes**\n\nThe timing suggests these were coordinated releases between OpenAI and Apple, bringing agentic AI capabilities deeply integrated into the Apple development ecosystem.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
