\n### 2. **Codex CLI (OpenAI)**\n- **Launch**: Originally open-sourced in April 2025, widely available by February 2026\n- **Features**: Lightweight terminal programming agent, multimodal support (can accept screenshots/drafts), natural language project development\n- **Compatibility**: Works with OpenAI's latest models (o3, o4-mini)\n- **Pricing**: Pay-per-use model based on token consumption\n\n### 3. **opencode**\n- **Status**: Available via npm and package managers (brew, pacman) in early 2026\n- **Description**: \"AI coding agent, built for the terminal\"\n- **Installation**: Available through multiple channels including npm, brew, and Arch Linux packages\n- **GitHub**: sst/opencode repository\n\n### 4. **GitHub Copilot CLI**\n- **Status**: Had public preview in late 2025, with Q1 2026 roadmap for enhanced features\n- **Planned Features**: Task priority queues, improved `/delegate` commands for async task processing\n\n## Industry Context for February 2026\n\nAccording to multiple sources from that time period:\n\n- **Major Shift**: 2026 marked the transition from \"autocomplete\" tools to \"autonomous agents\" in CLI environments\n- **CLI Renaissance**: Command-line interfaces became exciting again precisely because they're \"legacy\" technology that AI agents can natively and easily use\n- **Terminal-First Development**: The emphasis moved away from IDE plugins toward agentic execution directly in terminals\n- **Agent Capabilities**: These agents could install CLI tools (like Polymarket CLI or GitHub CLI), navigate repositories, manage issues/PRs, and build complete features\n\nThe search results show that February 2026 was indeed a pivotal time for CLI-based AI coding agents, with multiple mature products available and a clear industry trend toward terminal-first agentic development.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
