      "Based on the search results for open source AI coding agents and self-hosted solutions as of February 2026, here are the key findings:\n\n## Top Open Source AI Coding Agents\n\n### 1. **OpenCode**\n- **Stars**: 85,901 (gaining +44,137 in the past month)\n- **Description**: \"The open source coding agent\"\n- **Key Features**:\n  - Terminal-native (TUI) experience\n  - Lightweight and highly scalable\n  - Self-hosted - no dependency on specific cloud providers\n  - Supports multiple LLMs (Claude, OpenAI, Google Gemini, local LLMs)\n  - Dual-mode agent switching: \"build\" (full permissions) and \"plan\" (read-only analysis)\n  - Cross-platform desktop apps for macOS, Windows, and Linux\n  - Optimized for Neovim users and command-line enthusiasts\n  - Can handle code understanding, generation, modification, debugging, refactoring, and multi-step task planning\n\n### 2. **block/goose**\n- **Stars**: 27,594 (trending +491)\n- **Description**: \"an open source, extensible AI agent CLI\"\n- **Purpose**: Brings the power of Copilot coding agent directly to your terminal\n\n### 3. **OpenClaw**\n- **Description**: \"The open source coding agent\"\n- **Positioning**: Open-source \"Coding Agent Platform\"\n- **Focus**: Local, controllable personal AI assistant\n\n### 4. **Qwen Agent Framework**\n- **Repository**: QwenLM/Qwen3.5\n- **Description**: Open-source AI agent framework for building powerful LLM applications\n- **Capabilities**: Instruction following, tool usage, and planning\n- **Release Date**: February 2026\n\n## Industry Trends (February 2026)\n\nAccording to the GitHub trending data:\n\n1. **AI coding agents are becoming mainstream** - Terminal-native programming assistants like Claude Code that understand codebases and execute tasks naturally\n2. **Autonomous AI agents are emerging** - Self-directed applications like Pentagi (autonomous penetration testing) and GitNexus (browser-based code knowledge graph)\n3. **Self-hosted deployment is a priority** - Projects focusing on local control and reduced cloud dependencies\n4. **Development tools integration** - Deep integration with editors like Neovim and VSCode\n5. **Multi-model support** - Frameworks that work with various LLM providers and local models\n\nThe search results show a clear evolution from basic AI chat tools to sophisticated, deployable coding agents that can take over tasks and be used in production environments, with strong emphasis on self-hosting and local control."
